name: RecipeParse
role: component
intent: The recipe boundary (broker phase, unit 4) - the ONLY door through which authored YAML becomes a stag.Recipe the kernel will evaluate. One package, public, that parses, validates, lints, canonicalizes, and compiles in a single fail-closed pipeline: any violation of the format laws (Planning/08) or the graph laws (Planning/09) is a terminal error and NOTHING is compiled, canonicalized, hashed, or signed (reject-before-hash). The parser is the format's enforcement of "open at the edges, closed at the gate" at author time: it implements the 21 fail-closed parser rules distilled from the yaml.v3 threat research (aliases, merge keys, implicit typing, encoding smuggling, depth bombs), the per-kind key tables, and the author-time lint proofs (declare-before-use, forward-only known edges, reachability, guaranteed-Deny, unique fields, and the gate-protection proof). It produces the TWO hashes of decision 2: an artifact hash over the raw bytes as received (provenance) and a semantic hash over the parser-built canonical form (the signed contract, computed with the kernel's own stag.CanonicalHash so recipes and ReleaseEvents share ONE hashing discipline; the semantic hash is what a broker passes to Eval as recipeHash). CEILING: the linter proves structural laws over declared labels; it cannot judge whether a declared trust class or sink sensitivity is TRUE (the label-honesty contract, Planning/10) nor whether an in-policy value is a GOOD choice. Draft mode exists for authoring comfort; signing strictness never relaxes.
api:
  - "type Header struct { Name string; Version int64 }"
  - "type Parsed struct { Header Header; Recipe stag.Recipe; Rules map[string]stag.ReleaseRule; ArtifactHash string; SemanticHash string }"
  - "func Parse(src []byte) (Parsed, error)                    // strict / sign-time: warnings are errors"
  - "func ParseDraft(src []byte) (Parsed, []string, error)     // draft: hygiene findings return as warnings"
  - "var ErrNotImplemented error                               // foreach/exit: recognized vocabulary, distinct rejection"
behavior:
  - "PRELIMS (before yaml sees a byte, rules 1-4): input longer than 65536 bytes rejects; a UTF-8 BOM, a UTF-16 BOM (FE FF / FF FE), any NUL byte, or invalid UTF-8 rejects (yaml.v3 would silently transcode UTF-16 - refused here). The yaml decode targets *yaml.Node and is wrapped in recover(): any library panic becomes a parse error. The dependency is the maintained fork go.yaml.in/yaml/v3 (>= v3.0.4), pinned in go.mod; the kernel packages stay stdlib-only - the yaml dependency is quarantined in this package."
  - "DOCUMENT (rule 5): exactly one YAML document - the first Decode must succeed and the next must return io.EOF; a second document or trailing content rejects (yaml.Unmarshal would silently ignore it). An empty or null document rejects. The root must be a mapping."
  - "NODE HYGIENE (rules 6-11): the node tree is walked ITERATIVELY with a depth cap of 32 and a node cap of 10000 (yaml.v3 has no limits; deep nesting is a stack-kill). Any node with Anchor != \"\" or Kind == AliasNode rejects - INCLUDING an anchor on a mapping KEY (checked inline in the key loop, not only on popped value nodes; U4 adversarial finding), so billion-laughs and shared-node ambiguity die here; the format offers NO YAML-native reuse. Collection nodes carry a TAG allowlist too: a MappingNode tag must be \"\" or !!map and a SequenceNode tag must be \"\" or !!seq, so a custom or %TAG-expanded tag on a mapping/sequence (e.g. set: !custom [...]) rejects (U4 adversarial finding; scalar tags are allowlisted positionally elsewhere). The key text << and the !!merge tag reject wherever they appear (a plain <<: is a live merge even with aliases banned). Duplicate keys: yaml.v3's non-disableable uniqueKeys error is kept AND the walk runs its own byte-exact per-mapping check. Unknown keys reject at every level via closed key sets in the walk - NEVER via KnownFields, which cannot be enabled on Node.Decode at all."
  - "TAGS AND SCALARS (rules 9, 13-14; format laws 1-2, 4): every scalar is read as its RAW TEXT (node.Value); nothing ever decodes through interface{} and no yaml implicit typing produces a Go value. Tags are allowlisted POSITIONALLY: string positions accept only tag !!str (so a plain no/on/yes/5/2026-07-01 in a string position rejects - the error says to quote it); integer positions (version, min, max) accept only tag !!int AND the kernel-canonical text predicate (ParseInt base 10 succeeds AND text == FormatInt round-trip), so 0x1F, 014, 0o17, 1_000, +5, 007, 5.5, 1e3, .inf, and 09 all reject by construction; !!binary, !!timestamp, !!bool, !!float, !!null in any authored position and every custom or %TAG-expanded tag reject. Set members and the signed value are REQUIRED-QUOTED (style check), byte-exact, no trimming or normalization. Every string VALUE additionally rejects C0/C1 control characters (< 0x20, 0x7F, 0x80-0x9F) - a double-quote escape like \\t or \\0 decodes to a control byte that would ride verbatim into a signed ReleaseEvent field and line-inject a downstream text consumer, so the prelim raw-byte NUL guard is completed by a decoded-value control-char guard (U4 adversarial hardening; non-ASCII printable runes stay legal, homoglyph audit-confusion is a stated ceiling not a machine breach). No boolean-typed field exists anywhere in the schema; every flag is a closed string enum."
  - "KEYS AND NAMES (rules 10, format law 6): every map key is a ScalarNode with ShortTag !!str. Authored names obey closed ASCII grammars - ingredient names, slot names, and step ids match ^[a-z][a-z0-9_]{0,63}$; rule ids are 1-4 dot-separated segments of that grammar (e.g. routes.auto_approvable), 64 chars total max; the recipe name follows the step-id grammar. field and actor are free string VALUES recorded verbatim (actor vocabulary is decision 4). Homoglyphs, zero-width characters, uppercase, and empty keys are unrepresentable by grammar."
  - "TOP LEVEL: the root mapping's closed key set is {recipe, version, ingredients, rules, steps}; recipe, version, and steps are required; ingredients and rules are optional. version must equal exactly 1 (canonical int; version 2+ or quoted \"1\" rejects). steps must be a non-empty sequence."
  - "INGREDIENTS: a mapping name -> {origin (required, free string), trust (required, enum via stag.ParseTrustClass: untrusted/caller/authoritative)}. A value: key is UNKNOWN and rejects - the broker binds values at runtime; an authored value under trust: authoritative would smuggle trusted content past the binder. Caller-class ingredients are legal and may flow to authoritative sinks under a rule (decision 6)."
  - "RULES REGISTRY: a mapping id -> one release rule, kind via stag.ParseRuleKind (set_membership/signed_equality/numeric_range - the kernel-owned register, decision 1). Per-kind required/forbidden fields: set_membership requires set (non-empty sequence of quoted strings; duplicate members reject as author confusion) and forbids signed/min/max; signed_equality requires a non-empty quoted signed and forbids set/min/max; numeric_range requires min and max (canonical int64, min <= max) and forbids set/signed. The registry is the single diffable what-may-ever-be-released block (Planning/08 graft 5)."
  - "STEPS AND PER-KIND KEY TABLES (graft 2): every step is a mapping with required id (unique) and kind. The kind vocabulary: propose/sink/branch/gate compile (via stag.ParseNodeKind); foreach and exit are RECOGNIZED and reject with an error matching errors.Is(err, ErrNotImplemented), distinct from the unknown-kind rejection, and the file is never hashed (graft 3, reject-before-hash). Closed key sets per kind - any other key rejects, never zero-fills: propose {id, kind, out, goto?}; sink {id, kind, in, field, sensitivity, rule?, actor?, goto?} where sensitivity parses via stag.ParseSinkSensitivity, rule is legal ONLY on sensitivity authoritative (a rule on a benign sink rejects as dead policy), and actor is REQUIRED exactly when rule is present (the WHO dimension is never empty in a signed event); gate {id, kind, in, rule (required), on_fail?} - on_fail is the closed enum {deny, escalate}, absent means deny (the monotonic knob), and gate has NO goto key (the guarded segment begins at its fall-through successor); branch {id, kind, in, cases (required, non-empty sequence of {rule, goto}), default (required)} - branch edges are always explicit."
  - "DEFINITE ASSIGNMENT (Planning/09 declare-before-use, hardened after the U4 adversarial pass): document order is NOT enough - a propose out-slot is populated by Eval only when that propose EXECUTES, and a branch can skip a propose on the taken path, so a consumed slot must be defined on EVERY path to its consumer, not merely declared by an earlier step. The linter runs a fail-closed must-defined dataflow over the real edge graph (successors: branch case/default targets; propose/sink/gate goto or fall-through, a gate's pass path): entry(step) = intersection of exit(predecessors), seeded at the entry step with the ingredient names (ingredients are defined on all paths); exit adds a propose's out-slot. A sink/gate/branch whose in-slot is not in its entry set rejects. Equivalently the declaring propose must DOMINATE the consumer. This makes the lint law that an ACCEPTED recipe NEVER trips a kernel Fault true by construction (the kernel's severed-slot and branch-missing-slot backstops become unreachable on a parsed recipe). Runs after reachability, so every step but the entry has a predecessor."
  - "EDGES AND GRAPH LINT (Planning/09 laws): every in: resolves to a declared ingredient or an EARLIER step's out: (document-order pre-check for a clear undeclared-slot error; the definite-assignment pass above is the real safety proof); every rule: reference resolves in the registry, and the compiled Step.RuleID and Step.Rule are BOTH derived from that one registry entry (rule 20 - the parser's denormalization is the only binding of label to predicate); every goto/case-goto/default names an existing step id STRICTLY LATER in document order; duplicate step ids, duplicate out: slot names (including collision with an ingredient name), and duplicate sink field: strings (rule 19 - aliased fields collapse the event-to-crossing correspondence) all reject; every step must be REACHABLE from step 0 over the real edge semantics (fall-through where the previous step falls through, branch case/default edges, gate fall-through on pass) - an unreachable step rejects; an authoritative sink whose in-slot is statically non-authoritative (ingredient class or a propose output, which is always Untrusted) and that carries NO rule is a guaranteed-Deny sink and rejects (decision 5, the load-bearing lint)."
  - "GATE PROTECTION (the Planning/09 law 5 mechanism, pinned): the guarded segment of a gate G is the contiguous fall-through run starting at G's successor and ending at (inclusive) the first step that either carries an explicit goto, is a branch or gate, or is the last step. The linter proves NO explicit edge (goto, case goto, or default) targets ANY step inside a guarded segment - the only way in is through the gate. With goto forbidden on gates, the segment geometry is trivially single-entry; a recipe with an edge into a guarded segment rejects."
  - "MODES (decision 7): ParseDraft returns hygiene findings as warnings and still succeeds: an ingredient no step consumes, a registry rule no step references, and an empty string enumerated as a set member (legal declassifier data but suspicious - signed_equality already treats empty as unconfigured; rule 21). Parse (strict, the sign-time gate) treats every warning as an error. Everything else in this spec is a hard error in BOTH modes; signing strictness never relaxes and there is no lenient mode (rule 18)."
  - "TEACHING REJECTIONS (graft 4): the Ansible reflexes are refused BY NAME with the StAG alternative in the error text: when: (guarded transitions are the branch kind), loop:/with_items: (foreach, not yet implemented), register: (a propose out: slot), vars: (declared ingredients and release rules), notify:/become: (no handlers, no privilege escalation), on: (use in: - a plain on key is a YAML 1.1 boolean), and any scalar value containing {{ (no templating; values are data)."
  - "CANONICAL FORM AND THE TWO HASHES (decision 2, format law 9): after full validation the parser BUILDS the canonical form - never hashes anything yaml-decoded - from raw scalar texts using only string, int64, []any, and map[string]any: {recipe, version int64, ingredients {name:{origin, trust:<String name>}}, rules {id: {kind:<String name>, set sorted ascending / signed / min,max int64}}, steps: an ORDER-PRESERVING array, each step carrying only its kind-legal keys with enums by kernel String() names and on_fail as deny/escalate}. SemanticHash = stag.CanonicalHash(form) - the signed contract, and the recipeHash a broker passes to Eval. ArtifactHash = hex sha256 over the raw input bytes exactly as received. Comments and formatting therefore change ArtifactHash but never SemanticHash; any semantic edit changes both. A rejected file gets NEITHER hash (Parsed zero value + error)."
  - "COMPILE: Header{Name, Version}; Ingredients -> stag.Slot{Value: \"\", Class, Origin} (Value is never authorable); steps -> []stag.Step in document order with Kind/Out/In/Sensitivity/Field/Actor/Goto/Default from raw text, Escalate = (on_fail == escalate), Cases with each case's Rule a value-copy resolved from the registry, and sink Rule/RuleID both from the single referenced registry entry. Rules = the registry as value copies. The compiled Recipe evaluated by stag.Eval with SemanticHash reproduces the Planning/09 fixture semantics exactly."
  - "DETERMINISM AND ERRORS: identical input bytes yield identical Parsed (both hashes included) on every call. Every rejection is terminal and specific, carrying the yaml node line (and column where available) and naming the offending key/id/value; errors.Is distinguishes ErrNotImplemented. The parser never panics on ANY input (fuzz-proven): panics are recovered into errors."
constraints: package recipe at workspaces/stag/recipe (public; import path github.com/scanset/StAG/recipe). Depends on the stag root package (types, Parse inverses, CanonicalHash re-exports) and go.yaml.in/yaml/v3; stdlib otherwise (crypto/sha256, unicode/utf8, strconv, errors, fmt, regexp or hand-rolled grammar checks). The internal kernel packages stay untouched and stdlib-only.
